# Intuition
In this question we have to return maximum the sum of path between any 2 node. So, if we are present at root we have to compare between 3 entity :
1. Max path sum in left subtree(if exist).
2. Max path sum in right subtree(if exist).
3. sum of left, right subtree from node to root with root.

# Approach
Take helper function pathSum with return type pair<int, int> where first int store the maximum path sum between any two node in a tree and second int store the maximum path sum of any node from the root node either from the left sub tree or right subtree. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n) : As it traverse all nodes

- Space complexity:
O(n) : if tree is skew tree.
O(logn) : if tree is a binary tree.

# Abbreviation

1. lpsum : maximum path sum exist between any 2 nodes in left subtree
2. rpsum : maximum path sum exist between any 2 nodes in right subtree
3. lsum : maximum sum from node to root in left subtree.
4. rsum : maximum sum from node to root in right subtree.


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    pair<int, int> pathSum(TreeNode* root){
        if(root == NULL){
            return {INT_MIN, INT_MIN};
        }
        pair<int, int> leftchild = pathSum(root->left);
        pair<int, int> rightchild = pathSum(root->right);
        int lpsum = leftchild.first;
        int lsum = leftchild.second;
        int rpsum = rightchild.first;
        int rsum = rightchild.second;
        // if leftsum or rightsum is less than 0 then initialise as zero as we don't include that path in it
        if(lsum < 0){
            lsum = 0;
        }
        if(rsum < 0){
            rsum = 0;
        }
        int valu = lsum+rsum+root->val;
        int maxpsum = max(lpsum, max(rpsum, valu));
        return {maxpsum, max(lsum,rsum)+root->val};
    }
    int maxPathSum(TreeNode* root) {
        if(root == NULL){
            return 0;
        }
        pair<int, int> ans = pathSum(root);
        return ans.first;
    }
};
```

