# Intuition and Approach
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

Tokenizer concept please refer to this post
[Stop hating parsing problems and start having fun!](https://leetcode.com/problems/basic-calculator/solutions/2017431/stop-hating-parsing-problems-and-start-having-fun/)

Some solution are great, pretty short, beautiful and good performance,
but the more important thing to me is can I remember it in a interview several monthes after?

The concept should be very simple
if the number included sign, then the result is the summary of all numbers

    1 - 1 = 1 + (-1) 

Second thing is I have to deal with long numbers from string

    num = num * 10 + digit

Last is the expression `1 + 2 - (3 + 4)`
we can treat `(3 + 4)` as another `calculate("3+4")`

    1 + 2 - 7

Also, recursive actually is a call stack
in this case, recursive is as same as push the existing result to `stack`
and proceed from top by `pop` after expression result returned

And it's easy to find out one information missed when expression back,
we need to cache the `lastSign` in front of expression

    1 + 2 - (+ 3 + 4)
          ^: last sign

Extract parsing logic to Tokenizer seems let code longer,
but each function become simpler which means less mistake in interview
erasing the space by replacing also for the same purpose
we always can improve when the interview time is available

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$

# Code
```
class Tokenizer {
    let s: String
    var index: String.Index
    var lastSign = 1 // for expression back
    init(_ s: String) {
        self.s = s
        self.index = s.startIndex
    }

    func nextNum() -> Int {
        var num = 0
        var sign = 1
        if index < s.endIndex, "-+".contains(s[index]) {
            if s[index] == "-" { sign = -1 }
            next()
        }
        while index < s.endIndex, let n = Int(String(s[index])) {
            num = num * 10 + n
            next()
        }
        lastSign = sign
        return num * sign
    }

    func hasNext() -> Bool {
        index < s.endIndex
    }

    func next() {
        index = s.index(after: index)
    }

    func isExpressionStart() -> Bool {
        index < s.endIndex && s[index] == "("
    }

    func isExpressionEnd() -> Bool {
        index < s.endIndex && s[index] == ")"
    }
}

class Solution {
    func calculate(_ s: String) -> Int {
        // O(n), can move space handle to tokenizer for improvement
        let tokenizer = Tokenizer(s.replacingOccurrences(of: " ", with: ""))
        var calculateStack = [Int]()
        var signStack = [Int]()
        var result = 0
        while tokenizer.hasNext() {
            result += tokenizer.nextNum()
            // -(1+2), nextNum: 0 -> no impact to the result
            if tokenizer.isExpressionStart() {
                calculateStack.append(result)
                signStack.append(tokenizer.lastSign)
                result = 0
                tokenizer.next()
            } else if tokenizer.isExpressionEnd() {
                // 1+(1+2), stack: [1], result: 1 + 3
                // (1+1), stack: [0], result: 0 + 2
                // 2 - 3 + (1 + 4) stack: -1, sign: 1
                // 2 - 3 - (1 + 1) stack: -1, sign: -1
                result = calculateStack.removeLast() + result * signStack.removeLast()
                tokenizer.next()
            }
        }
        return result
    }
}
```

